# VI Editor Shortcuts (Quick Reference)

The VI editor is a powerful tool for editing configuration files and scripts in Linux.  
This document provides **key modes**, **commands**, and **shortcuts** used in daily work.

---

## 1. Management Area: VI / VIM Editor

---

## 2. Definition – What VI Editor Manages

VI manages:

- File editing  
- Navigation within files  
- Searching and replacing text  
- Copying, pasting, deleting lines  
- Working with multiple files and splits  

It is widely used by system administrators and DevOps engineers.

---

## 3. Commands List

---

### Modes in VI

| Mode | Used For |
|------|----------|
| **Normal mode** | Navigation & commands |
| **Insert mode** | Text editing |
| **Command mode** | Saving, quitting, searching |

---

### Enter/Exit Modes

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `i` | Insert before cursor |
| `a` | Append after cursor |
| `o` | Open new line below |
| `O` | Open new line above |
| `Esc` | Exit insert mode |

---

### Navigation Shortcuts

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `h` | Move left |
| `l` | Move right |
| `j` | Move down |
| `k` | Move up |
| `0` | Move to line start |
| `$` | Move to line end |
| `w` | Next word |
| `b` | Previous word |
| `gg` | Go to file start |
| `G` | Go to file end |
| `:n` | Go to line number n |

---

### Editing Shortcuts

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `x` | Delete character |
| `dd` | Delete line |
| `dw` | Delete word |
| `yy` | Copy line |
| `yw` | Copy word |
| `p` | Paste after cursor |
| `P` | Paste before cursor |
| `u` | Undo |
| `Ctrl + r` | Redo |

---

### Search & Replace

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `/text` | Search forward |
| `?text` | Search backward |
| `n` | Repeat search |
| `N` | Repeat reverse search |
| `:%s/old/new/g` | Replace all occurrences |
| `:s/old/new/g` | Replace in current line |

---

### Save & Quit

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `:w` | Save |
| `:q` | Quit |
| `:wq` | Save & quit |
| `:q!` | Quit without saving |

---

## Summary

- VI is essential for editing system files.  
- Learn navigation, editing, and saving commands for efficient usage.

